on, according to which Christians, Jews, and others occupied legitimate places in Iranian political culture in positions subordinate to the imperial religion. Christians, for their part, positioned themselves in a political culture not of their own making, with recourse to their own ideological and institutional resources, ranging from the writing of saints’ lives to the judicial arbitration of bishops. In placing the social history of East Syrian Christians at the center of the Iranian imperial story, A State of Mixture helps explain the endurance of a culturally diverse empire across four centuries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChristianity and other religionsxZoroastrianism. 0aChristianity and politicszIranxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aChristianszIranxSocial conditions. 0aZoroastrianismxRelationsxChristianity. 7aRELIGION / Ancient.2bisacsh  aancient middle eastern religions.  aancient persia.  aancient political systems.  aancient religions.  achristian inclusion in late antiquity.  achristian law.  achristianity and politics.  achristianity.  achristians in iran.  acomparative religion.  aearly iranian civilization.  ahistory of religion in iran.  airanian political practice.  amonotheistic religions.  areligion in the mediterranean.  areligion in the near east.  areligion.  areligions of persia.  azoroastrian empire.  azoroastrianism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028619140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096153140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520961531423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520961531/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP